# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: marianne-gullberg
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The **Academia Europaea** is a pan-European academy of humanities, letters, law, and sciences.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The Academia was founded in 1988 as a functioning Europe-wide Academy that encompasses all fields of scholarly inquiry.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] It acts as co-ordinator of European interests in national research agencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The concept of a 'European Academy of Sciences' was raised at a meeting in Paris of the European Ministers of Science in 1985.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The meeting also included Brian Flowers and John Kendrew.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] In October 1986 a larger meeting with participants representing some countries in the Council of Europe supported the development of a European academy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The name *Academia Europaea* was decided on in a meeting in December 1987 as a "linguistically neutral" name.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The foundation meeting was held in Cambridge in September 1988 and Arnold Burgen became the first president of the academy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Hubert Curien, who was at that time the French Minister of Science (and later became the second President of the Academia), gave the inaugural address and provided the active support of the French government.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The first Plenary Meeting was held in London in June 1989, by which time there were 627 members.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The Royal Society supported Academia Europaea financially as it worked to secure broader funding.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Since 1989, the Academia Europaea has evolved from its origins as an organization of predominantly "western European" scholars into a pan-European Academy of Sciences, Humanities and Letters.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The funding of the Academy is based on an original endowment, contributions from some of the member countries, special projects and by other organizations like the Leopoldina, which is also supporting the Academia Europaea financially.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] When the European Academies' Science Advisory Council was founded, Academia Europaea became a member.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] It does not aim to replace existing national academies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The objectives were kept deliberately broad, covering the humanities, social and natural sciences, so as to ensure interdisciplinary discourse and activities.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Initial activities were to include annual meetings of members, multidisciplinary meetings, an interdisciplinary journal, a newsletter, providing independent advice, improving mobility of scholars within Europe and improving public understanding of science.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Academia Europaea covers a range of subjects, including law, humanities, social sciences, physical sciences, religion and history.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Impact has been achieved through workshop meetings and reports, for instance to committees under the Council of Europe, on topics such as education, psychosocial problems among the youth, and the development of research academies in specific parts of Europe.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The scholarly interests of the Academia are managed through a section structure.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] On election, all members are assigned to a section.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The Academia elects members from 47 Council of Europe states in recognition of their academic achievements.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Election to the membership has been celebrated by several institutions as an honour each year.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Elected members are entitled to the post-nominal letters **MAE**.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] SAPEA pulls together scientific expertise from the pan-European Academia and more than 100 European national academies from over 40 countries, collectively providing independent policy advice to the European Commissioners.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The Academia serves as official advisor to the European Union under the Scientific Advice Mechanism.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The Academia Europaea has published *European Review* (*ER*) since 1993 on behalf of members and in conjunction with Cambridge University Press (since 1998).
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] It is a quarterly, peer-reviewed, international journal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Editorial control is in the hands of an independent board.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] *European Review* publishes articles and reviews that will be of broad interest to an intellectual readership, world-wide.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] Contributions come from academics, professionals and those in public life and address multidisciplinary and interdisciplinary issues across the sciences arts, humanities and letters.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] *European Review* provides the AE with a vehicle for publication of articles from sponsored conferences and workshops.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The editorial board invites contributions and reviews from opinion leaders world-wide.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] *European Review* has become available fully on-line.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] The registered office and headquarters of the Academia Europaea is in London.
[src:marianne-gullberg/academia-europaea] This is also the location of the General Secretariat.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Kendon was born on 4 April 1934 in London, son of the writer Frank Kendon and Elizabeth Cecilia Phyllis Horne, a school teacher.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] At the University of Cambridge, he read Botany, Zoology and Human Physiology, as well as Experimental Psychology for the Natural Sciences.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] At the University of Oxford, he studied Experimental Psychology, focusing on the temporal organization of utterances in conversation, using Eliot Chapple's chronography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Then he moved to Cornell University to study directly with Chapple on research leading to his D.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] His thesis topic—communication conduct in face-to-face interaction—spelled out the interests he would pursue in subsequent decades.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He is noted for his study of gesture and sign languages and how these relate to spoken language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Phil., he accepted a position in the Institute of Experimental Psychology at Oxford, where he worked in a research group with Michael Argyle and E.R.W.F.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He initially focused on sign systems in Papua New Guinea and Australian Aboriginal sign languages, before developing a general framework for understanding gestures with the same kind of rigorous semiotic analysis as has been previously applied to spoken language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Important influences on his theoretical understandings included: Erving Goffman, Albert Scheflen, Ray Birdwhistell, and Gregory Bateson.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Becoming aware of Scheflen's work in 1965, while still at Oxford, he managed to meet him in Philadelphia, where he shared his earliest work; as a result, he was first invited to join William S.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Condon's research team at the Western Psychiatric Institute and Clinic in 1966-67, and then to join Scheflen's research team at Bronx State Hospital in 1967.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He never actually worked with Birdwhistell directly, but they were in contact, and he did work with films made available to him by Birdwhistell.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In 1976 he took up an appointment in Canberra, Australia at the Department of Anthropology in the Research School of Pacific Studies, Australian National University.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He undertook filming everyday interaction in Papua New Guinea but also was able to record a sign language in use in the valley where he worked where there was a considerable number of deaf persons.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] His publication of this work, in three articles in 1980, proved to be a pioneering study; no other accounts on sign language from this part of the world were to appear until the beginning of the twenty-first century.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] This work was republished as a monograph together with a new essay written by colleagues bringing the original work up to date.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] After this he undertook a major investigation of the sign languages in use among indigenous Australians - these are sign languages used for ritual reasons or for practical reasons in situations where speech might is impractical or inappropriate.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] These are known as alternate sign languages, distinguishing them from primary sign languages developed among deaf people.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Extensive documentation of his research in Australia is available at the library of the Australian Institute of Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Studies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In 1988, he returned to Philadelphia, teaching for two years at the Annenberg School for Communication at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Kendon then moved to Naples, Italy and undertook fieldwork on the use of gesture in everyday interaction among Neapolitans and also published a translation of a 19th Century book about Neapolitan gesture (by Andrea de Jorio), comparing it to gesturing among the Greeks and Romans.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In 2004 he published an important general book on the phenomena of gesture which drew extensively on his work in Naples as well as his work in New Guinea and Australia, the United States and the United Kingdom.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Since then he has published various articles on gesture and related topics, including discussions of the place of gesture in theories about language origins.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In 2012, he returned to Cambridge, where he spent the rest of his life, associated with the Division of Biological Anthropology at Cambridge, and an Honorary Professor in Psychology and Language Sciences at University College London.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Kendon received research grants from the National Science Foundation, the Wenner-Gren Foundation for Anthropological Research, the American Council of Learned Societies, as well as a Guggenheim Fellowship.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In addition to teaching at Oxford and Penn, he held positions at Cornell University and Connecticut College in the US, as well as the Università degli Studi di Napoli "L'Orientale", the University of Salerno and the University of Calabria in Italy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Kendon was a founding editor of the journal *GESTURE* (published by John Benjamins of Amsterdam), along with Cornelia Müller, in 2000.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He was the sole editor from 2010 to April 2017, when he was replaced by Sotaro Kita.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] In his role as editor of *GESTURE* he was an Ex Officio member of the board of the International Society for Gesture Studies, of which he was elected Honorary President in 2006.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] He edited the book series *Gesture Studies* for John Benjamins, with 9 volumes published between 2007 and 2022.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Colleagues prepared a festschrift in 2014, honoring his contribution to the study of gestures and interaction.
[src:marianne-gullberg/adam-kendon] Kendon married Margaret Rhoads in 1961; they had three children, Gudrun, Benjamin and Angus.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] Özyürek was born in Turkey, and took her BA in psychology at Boğaziçi University.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] She received her joint PhD in linguistics and developmental psychology from the University of Chicago in 2000, before moving to Koç University in Istanbul to take up an assistant professorship in psychology.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] From 2003 to 2007 she was a postdoctoral researcher at the Donders Center for Cognitive Neuroimaging in Nijmegen.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] In 2007 she was appointed associate professor in the Department of Linguistics at Radboud University Nijmegen, and was promoted to full professor in 2010.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] In 2019, Özyürek was elected Member of the Academia Europaea.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] In 2022 she was appointed Director of the new Multimodal Language Department at the Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics, where she builds on her previous work at the Radboud University’s Multimodal Language and Cognition Lab.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] Özyürek is a psycholinguist and neurolinguist who approaches the human capacity for language from the perspective of multimodality and nonverbal communication.
[src:marianne-gullberg/aslı-özyürek] She has worked extensively on gesture and on signed languages, using the methods of corpus linguistics and experimental linguistics among others.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Voltage fluctuations measured by the EEG bio amplifier and electrodes allow the evaluation of normal brain activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] As the electrical activity monitored by EEG originates in neurons in the underlying brain tissue, the recordings made by the electrodes on the surface of the scalp vary in accordance with their orientation and distance to the source of the activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Furthermore, the value recorded is distorted by intermediary tissues and bones, which act in a manner akin to resistors and capacitors in an electrical circuit.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This means that not all neurons will contribute equally to an EEG signal, with an EEG predominately reflecting the activity of cortical neurons near the electrodes on the scalp.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Deep structures within the brain further away from the electrodes will not contribute directly to an EEG; these include the base of the cortical gyrus, medial walls of the major lobes, hippocampus, thalamus, and brain stem.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] A healthy human EEG will show certain patterns of activity that correlate with how awake a person is.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The range of frequencies one observes are between 1 and 30 Hz, and amplitudes will vary between 20 and 100 μV.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The observed frequencies are subdivided into various groups: alpha (8–13 Hz), beta (13–30 Hz), delta (0.5–4 Hz), and theta (4–7 Hz).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Alpha waves are observed when a person is in a state of relaxed wakefulness and are mostly prominent over the parietal and occipital sites.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] During intense mental activity, beta waves are more prominent in frontal areas as well as other regions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] If a relaxed person is told to open their eyes, one observes alpha activity decreasing and an increase in beta activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Theta and delta waves are not generally seen in wakefulness – if they are, it is a sign of brain dysfunction.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG can detect abnormal electrical discharges such as sharp waves, spikes, or spike-and-wave complexes, as observable in people with epilepsy; thus, it is often used to inform medical diagnosis.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG can detect the onset and spatio-temporal (location and time) evolution of seizures and the presence of status epilepticus.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] It is also used to help diagnose sleep disorders, depth of anesthesia, coma, encephalopathies, cerebral hypoxia after cardiac arrest, and brain death.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG used to be a first-line method of diagnosis for tumors, stroke, and other focal brain disorders, but this use has decreased with the advent of high-resolution anatomical imaging techniques such as magnetic resonance imaging (MRI) and computed tomography (CT).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Despite its limited spatial resolution, EEG continues to be a valuable tool for research and diagnosis.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] It is one of the few mobile techniques available and offers millisecond-range temporal resolution, which is not possible with CT, PET, or MRI.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Derivatives of the EEG technique include evoked potentials (EP), which involves averaging the EEG activity time-locked to the presentation of a stimulus of some sort (visual, somatosensory, or auditory).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Event-related potentials (ERPs) refer to averaged EEG responses that are time-locked to more complex processing of stimuli; this technique is used in cognitive science, cognitive psychology, and psychophysiological research.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG is the gold standard diagnostic procedure to confirm epilepsy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The sensitivity of a routine EEG to detect interictal epileptiform discharges at epilepsy centers has been reported to be in the range of 29–55%.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Given the low to moderate sensitivity, a routine EEG (typically with a duration of 20–30 minutes) can be normal in people that have epilepsy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] When a routine EEG is normal and there is a high suspicion or need to confirm epilepsy, it may be repeated or performed with a longer duration in the epilepsy monitoring unit (EMU) or at home with an ambulatory EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In addition, there are activating maneuvers such as photic stimulation, hyperventilation and sleep deprivation that can increase the diagnostic yield of the EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] At times, a routine EEG is not sufficient to establish the diagnosis or determine the best course of action in terms of treatment.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In this case, attempts may be made to record an EEG while a seizure is occurring.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This is known as an ictal recording, as opposed to an interictal recording, which refers to the EEG recording between seizures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] To obtain an ictal recording, a prolonged EEG is typically performed accompanied by a time-synchronized video and audio recording.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This can be done either as an outpatient (at home) or during a hospital admission, preferably to an Epilepsy Monitoring Unit (EMU) with nurses and other personnel trained in the care of patients with seizures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Outpatient ambulatory video EEGs typically last one to three days.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] An admission to an Epilepsy Monitoring Unit typically lasts several days but may last for a week or longer.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] While in the hospital, seizure medications are usually withdrawn to increase the odds that a seizure will occur during admission.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] For reasons of safety, medications are not withdrawn during an EEG outside of the hospital.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Ambulatory video EEGs, therefore, have the advantage of convenience and are less expensive than a hospital admission, but they also have the disadvantage of a decreased probability of recording a clinical event.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In cases of epileptic seizures, continuous EEG monitoring helps to characterize seizures and localize/lateralize the region of the brain from which a seizure originates.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This can help identify appropriate non-medication treatment options.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In clinical use, EEG traces are visually analyzed by neurologists to look at various features.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Increasingly, quantitative analysis of EEG is being used in conjunction with visual analysis.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In cases where significant brain injury is suspected, e.g., after cardiac arrest, EEG can provide some prognostic information.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] If a patient with epilepsy is being considered for resective surgery to treat epilepsy, it is often necessary to localize the focus (source) of the epileptic brain activity with a resolution greater than what is provided by scalp EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In these cases, neurosurgeons typically implant strips and grids of electrodes or penetrating depth electrodes under the dura mater, through either a craniotomy or a burr hole.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The recording of these signals is referred to as electrocorticography (ECoG), subdural EEG (SDE), intracranial EEG (iEEG), or stereotactic EEG (SEEG).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The signal recorded from ECoG is on a different scale of activity than the brain activity recorded from scalp EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Low-voltage, high-frequency components that cannot be seen easily (or at all) in scalp EEG can be seen clearly in ECoG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Further, smaller electrodes (which cover a smaller parcel of brain surface) allow for better spatial resolution to narrow down the areas critical for seizure onset and propagation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Some clinical sites record data from penetrating microelectrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Sometimes it is more convenient or clinically necessary to perform ambulatory EEG recordings in the home of the person being tested.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These studies typically have a duration of 24–72 hours.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG and the related study of ERPs are used extensively in neuroscience, cognitive science, cognitive psychology, neurolinguistics, and psychophysiological research, as well as to study human functions such as swallowing.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Any EEG techniques used in research are not sufficiently standardised for clinical use, and many ERP studies fail to report all of the necessary processing steps for data collection and reduction, limiting the reproducibility and replicability of many studies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Based on a 2024 systematic literature review and meta analysis commissioned by the Patient-Centered Outcomes Research Institute (PCORI), EEG scans cannot be used reliably to assist in making a clinical diagnosis of ADHD.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] However, EEG continues to be used in research on mental disabilities, such as auditory processing disorder (APD), ADD, and ADHD.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEGs have also been studied for their utility in detecting neurophysiological changes in the brain after concussion, however, at this time there are no advanced imaging techniques that can be used clinically to diagnose or monitor recovery from concussion.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Despite the relatively poor spatial sensitivity of EEG, the "one-dimensional signals from localised peripheral regions on the head make it attractive for its simplistic fidelity and has allowed high clinical and basic research throughput".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] While challenging, these have been successfully overcome in a number of studies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] MRI's produce detailed images created by generating strong magnetic fields that may induce potentially harmful displacement force and torque.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These fields produce potentially harmful radio frequency heating and create image artifacts rendering images useless.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Due to these potential risks, only certain medical devices can be used in an MR environment.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Recently, a combined EEG/MEG (EMEG) approach has been investigated for the purpose of source reconstruction in epilepsy diagnosis.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG has also been combined with positron emission tomography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This provides the advantage of allowing researchers to see what EEG signals are associated with different drug actions in the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The brain's electrical charge is maintained by billions of neurons.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Neurons are electrically charged (or "polarized") by membrane transport proteins that pump ions across their membranes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Neurons are constantly exchanging ions with the extracellular milieu, for example to maintain resting potential and to propagate action potentials.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Ions of similar charge repel each other, and when many ions are pushed out of many neurons at the same time, they can push their neighbours, who push their neighbours, and so on, in a wave.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This process is known as volume conduction.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] When the wave of ions reaches the electrodes on the scalp, they can push or pull electrons on the metal in the electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Since metal conducts the push and pull of electrons easily, the difference in push or pull voltages between any two electrodes can be measured by a voltmeter.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Recording these voltages over time gives us the EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The electric potential generated by an individual neuron is far too small to be picked up by EEG or MEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG activity therefore always reflects the summation of the synchronous activity of thousands or millions of neurons that have similar spatial orientation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] If the cells do not have similar spatial orientation, their ions do not line up and create waves to be detected.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Pyramidal neurons of the cortex are thought to produce the most EEG signal because they are well-aligned and fire together.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Because voltage field gradients fall off with the square of distance, activity from deep sources is more difficult to detect than currents near the skull.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Scalp EEG activity shows oscillations at a variety of frequencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Several of these oscillations have characteristic frequency ranges, spatial distributions and are associated with different states of brain functioning (e.g., waking and the various sleep stages).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These oscillations represent synchronized activity over a network of neurons.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The neuronal networks underlying some of these oscillations are understood (e.g., the thalamocortical resonance underlying sleep spindles), while many others are not (e.g., the system that generates the posterior basic rhythm).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Research that measures both EEG and neuron spiking finds the relationship between the two is complex, with a combination of EEG power in the gamma band and phase in the delta band relating most strongly to neuron spike activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In conventional scalp EEG, the recording is obtained by placing electrodes on the scalp with a conductive gel or paste, usually after preparing the scalp area by light abrasion to reduce impedance due to dead skin cells.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Many systems typically use electrodes, each of which is attached to an individual wire.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Some systems use caps or nets into which electrodes are embedded; this is particularly common when high-density arrays of electrodes are needed.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Electrode locations and names are specified by the International 10–20 system for most clinical and research applications (except when high-density arrays are used).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This system ensures that the naming of electrodes is consistent across laboratories.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In most clinical applications, 19 recording electrodes (plus ground and system reference) are used.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] A smaller number of electrodes are typically used when recording EEG from neonates.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Additional electrodes can be added to the standard set-up when a clinical or research application demands increased spatial resolution for a particular area of the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] High-density arrays (typically via cap or net) can contain up to 256 electrodes more-or-less evenly spaced around the scalp.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Each electrode is connected to one input of a differential amplifier (one amplifier per pair of electrodes); a common system reference electrode is connected to the other input of each differential amplifier.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These amplifiers amplify the voltage between the active electrode and the reference (typically 1,000–100,000 times, or 60–100 dB of power gain).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In analog EEG, the signal is then filtered (next paragraph), and the EEG signal is output as the deflection of pens as paper passes underneath.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Most EEG systems these days, however, are digital, and the amplified signal is digitized via an analog-to-digital converter, after being passed through an anti-aliasing filter.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Analog-to-digital sampling typically occurs at 256–512 Hz in clinical scalp EEG; sampling rates of up to 20 kHz are used in some research applications.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] During the recording, a series of activation procedures may be used.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These procedures may induce normal or abnormal EEG activity that might not otherwise be seen.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] These procedures include hyperventilation, photic stimulation (with a strobe light), eye closure, mental activity, sleep and sleep deprivation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] During (inpatient) epilepsy monitoring, a patient's typical seizure medications may be withdrawn.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The digital EEG signal is stored electronically and can be filtered for display.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Typical settings for the high-pass filter and a low-pass filter are 0.5–1 Hz and 35–70 Hz respectively.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The high-pass filter typically filters out slow artifact, such as electrogalvanic signals and movement artifact, whereas the low-pass filter filters out high-frequency artifacts, such as electromyographic signals.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] An additional notch filter is typically used to remove artifact caused by electrical power lines (60 Hz in the United States and 50 Hz in many other countries).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The EEG signals can be captured with opensource hardware such as OpenBCI and the signal can be processed by freely available EEG software such as EEGLAB or the Neurophysiological Biomarker Toolbox.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] As part of an evaluation for epilepsy surgery, it may be necessary to insert electrodes near the surface of the brain, under the surface of the dura mater.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This is accomplished via burr hole or craniotomy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This is referred to variously as "electrocorticography (ECoG)", "intracranial EEG (I-EEG)" or "subdural EEG (SD-EEG)".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Depth electrodes may also be placed into brain structures, such as the amygdala or hippocampus, structures, which are common epileptic foci and may not be "seen" clearly by scalp EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The electrocorticographic signal is processed in the same manner as digital scalp EEG (above), with a couple of caveats.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] ECoG is typically recorded at higher sampling rates than scalp EEG because of the requirements of Nyquist theorem – the subdural signal is composed of a higher predominance of higher frequency components.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Also, many of the artifacts that affect scalp EEG do not impact ECoG, and therefore display filtering is often not needed.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] A typical adult human EEG signal is about 10 μV to 100 μV in amplitude when measured from the scalp.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Since an EEG voltage signal represents a difference between the voltages at two electrodes, the display of the EEG for the reading electroencephalographer may be set up in one of several ways.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Each channel (i.e., waveform) represents the difference between two adjacent electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The entire montage consists of a series of these channels.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] For example, the channel "Fp1-F3" represents the difference in voltage between the Fp1 electrode and the F3 electrode.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The next channel in the montage, "F3-C3", represents the voltage difference between F3 and C3, and so on through the entire array of electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Each channel represents the difference between a certain electrode and a designated reference electrode.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] There is no standard position for this reference; it is, however, at a different position than the "recording" electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Midline positions are often used because they do not amplify the signal in one hemisphere vs. the other, such as Cz, Oz, Pz etc. as online reference.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The outputs of all of the amplifiers are summed and averaged, and this averaged signal is used as the common reference for each channel.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Each channel represents the difference between an electrode and a weighted average of the surrounding electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] When analog (paper) EEGs are used, the technologist switches between montages during the recording in order to highlight or better characterize certain features of the EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] With digital EEG, all signals are typically digitized and stored in a particular (usually referential) montage; since any montage can be constructed mathematically from any other, the EEG can be viewed by the electroencephalographer in any display montage that is desired.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The EEG is read by a clinical neurophysiologist or neurologist (depending on local custom and law regarding medical specialities), optimally one who has specific training in the interpretation of EEGs for clinical purposes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This is done by visual inspection of the waveforms, called graphoelements.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The use of computer signal processing of the EEG – so-called quantitative electroencephalography – is somewhat controversial when used for clinical purposes (although there are many research uses).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In the early 1990s Babak Taheri, at University of California, Davis demonstrated the first single and also multichannel dry active electrode arrays using micro-machining.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The single channel dry EEG electrode construction and results were published in 1994.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The arrayed electrode was also demonstrated to perform well compared to silver/silver chloride electrodes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The device consisted of four sites of sensors with integrated electronics to reduce noise by impedance matching.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The advantages of such electrodes are: (1) no electrolyte used, (2) no skin preparation, (3) significantly reduced sensor size, and (4) compatibility with EEG monitoring systems.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The active electrode array is an integrated system made of an array of capacitive sensors with local integrated circuitry housed in a package with batteries to power the circuitry.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This level of integration was required to achieve the functional performance obtained by the electrode.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The electrode was tested on an electrical test bench and on human subjects in four modalities of EEG activity, namely: (1) spontaneous EEG, (2) sensory event-related potentials, (3) brain stem potentials, and (4) cognitive event-related potentials.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The performance of the dry electrode compared favorably with that of the standard wet electrodes in terms of skin preparation, no gel requirements (dry), and higher signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In 1999 researchers at Case Western Reserve University, in Cleveland, Ohio, led by Hunter Peckham, used 64-electrode EEG skullcap to return limited hand movements to quadriplegic Jim Jatich.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] As Jatich concentrated on simple but opposite concepts like up and down, his beta-rhythm EEG output was analysed using software to identify patterns in the noise.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] A basic pattern was identified and used to control a switch: Above average activity was set to on, below average off.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] As well as enabling Jatich to control a computer cursor the signals were also used to drive the nerve controllers embedded in his hands, restoring some movement.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In 2018, a functional dry electrode composed of a polydimethylsiloxane elastomer filled with conductive carbon nanofibers was reported.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG technology often involves applying a gel to the scalp which facilitates strong signal-to-noise ratio.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This results in more reproducible and reliable experimental results.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Since patients dislike having their hair filled with gel, and the lengthy setup requires trained staff on hand, utilizing EEG outside the laboratory setting can be difficult.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Additionally, it has been observed that wet electrode sensors' performance reduces after a span of hours.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Therefore, research has been directed to developing dry and semi-dry EEG bioelectronic interfaces.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Hybrid dry–wet EEG electrode systems have also been developed to combine the rapid setup of dry electrodes with the signal stability of gel-based recordings.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] One example is the g.SAHARA Hybrid EEG electrode system, developed by g.tec medical engineering GmbH, an Austria-based neurotechnology company.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The system uses active electrodes made of a conductive polymer with multiple pins designed to maintain contact through hair, allowing EEG recordings to be performed either without gel or with optional conductive gel applied through a central opening.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This hybrid approach is intended to reduce electrode–skin impedance while preserving setup flexibility, and it has been used in research settings across standard EEG positions defined by the international 10–20 system.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Dry electrode signals depend upon mechanical contact.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Therefore, it can be difficult getting a usable signal because of impedance between the skin and the electrode.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Some EEG systems attempt to circumvent this issue by applying a saline solution.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Others have a semi dry nature and release small amounts of the gel upon contact with the scalp.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Another solution uses spring loaded pin setups.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] They may also be dangerous if they were used in a situation where a patient could bump their head since they could become lodged after an impact trauma incident.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Currently, headsets are available incorporating dry electrodes with up to 30 channels.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Such designs are able to compensate for some of the signal quality degradation related to high impedances by optimizing pre-amplification, shielding and supporting mechanics.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Most important is its poor spatial resolution.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG is most sensitive to a particular set of post-synaptic potentials: those generated in superficial layers of the cortex, on the crests of gyri directly abutting the skull and radial to the skull.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Dendrites which are deeper in the cortex, inside sulci, in midline or deep structures (such as the cingulate gyrus or hippocampus), or producing currents that are tangential to the skull, make far less contribution to the EEG signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG recordings do not directly capture axonal action potentials.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] An action potential can be accurately represented as a current quadrupole, meaning that the resulting field decreases more rapidly than the ones produced by the current dipole of post-synaptic potentials.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In addition, since EEGs represent averages of thousands of neurons, a large population of cells in synchronous activity is necessary to cause a significant deflection on the recordings.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Action potentials are very fast and, as a consequence, the chances of field summation are slim.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] However, neural backpropagation, as a typically longer dendritic current dipole, can be picked up by EEG electrodes and is a reliable indication of the occurrence of neural output.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Not only do EEGs capture dendritic currents almost exclusively as opposed to axonal currents, they also show a preference for activity on populations of parallel dendrites and transmitting current in the same direction at the same time.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Pyramidal neurons of cortical layers II/III and V extend apical dendrites to layer I.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Currents moving up or down these processes underlie most of the signals produced by electroencephalography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG thus provides information with a large bias in favor of particular neuron types, locations and orientations.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] So it generally should not be used to make claims about global brain activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The meninges, cerebrospinal fluid and skull "smear" the EEG signal, obscuring its intracranial source.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] It is mathematically impossible to reconstruct a unique intracranial current source for a given EEG signal, as some currents produce potentials that cancel each other out.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] This is referred to as the inverse problem.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] However, much work has been done to produce remarkably good estimates of, at least, a localized electric dipole that represents the recorded currents.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG has several strong points as a tool for exploring brain activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG have excellent temporal resolution and can detect changes over milliseconds, which is particularly useful to assess a reaction to a stimulus considering an action potential takes approximately 0.5–130 milliseconds to propagate across a single neuron, depending on the type of neuron.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Other methods of looking at brain activity, such as PET, fMRI or fUS have time resolution between seconds and minutes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG measures the brain's electrical activity directly, while other methods record changes in blood flow (e.g., SPECT, fMRI, fUS) or metabolic activity (e.g., PET, NIRS), which are indirect markers of brain electrical activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] There are technical difficulties associated with combining EEG and fMRI including the need to remove the *MRI gradient artifact* present during MRI acquisition.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Furthermore, currents can be induced in moving EEG electrode wires due to the magnetic field of the MRI.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG can be used simultaneously with NIRS or fUS without major technical difficulties.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] There is no influence of these modalities on each other and a combined measurement can give useful information about electrical activity as well as hemodynamics at medium spatial resolution.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG is also frequently combined with functional near-infrared spectroscopy (fNIRS) to enable simultaneous measurement of fast neuronal electrical activity and slower hemodynamic responses associated with neurovascular coupling.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] In such multimodal approaches, EEG provides millisecond-level temporal resolution, while fNIRS contributes complementary information on changes in oxygenated and deoxygenated hemoglobin with moderate spatial resolution.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] Combined EEG–fNIRS measurements can be performed without major technical interference between modalities and are therefore well suited for studies conducted outside highly controlled imaging environments.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] EEG reflects correlated synaptic activity caused by post-synaptic potentials of cortical neurons.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] The ionic currents involved in the generation of fast action potentials may not contribute greatly to the averaged field potentials representing the EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p01] More specifically, the scalp electrical potentials that produce EEG are generally thought to be caused by the extracellular ionic currents caused by dendritic electrical activity, whereas the fields producing magnetoencephalographic signals are associated with intracellular ionic currents.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG is typically described in terms of (1) rhythmic activity and (2) transients.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The rhythmic activity is divided into bands by frequency.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Frequency bands are usually extracted using spectral methods (for instance Welch) as implemented for instance in freely available EEG software such as EEGLAB or the Neurophysiological Biomarker Toolbox.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Computational processing of the EEG is often named quantitative electroencephalography (qEEG).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Most of the cerebral signal observed in the scalp EEG falls in the range of 1–20 Hz (activity below or above this range is likely to be artifactual, under standard clinical recording techniques).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Waveforms are subdivided into bandwidths known as alpha, beta, theta, and delta to signify the majority of the EEG used in clinical practice.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The practice of using only whole numbers in the definitions comes from practical considerations in the days when only whole cycles could be counted on paper records.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] This leads to gaps in the definitions, as seen elsewhere on this page.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The theoretical definitions have always been more carefully defined to include all frequencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Unfortunately there is no agreement in standard reference works on what these ranges should be– values for the upper end of alpha and lower end of beta include 12, 13, 14 and 15.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] If the threshold is taken as 14 Hz, then the slowest beta wave has about the same duration as the longest spike (70 ms), which makes this the most useful value.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] cortical areas) that emerges when the hands and arms are idle; and the "third rhythm" (alpha activity in the temporal or frontal lobes).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Alpha can be abnormal; for example, an EEG that has diffuse alpha occurring in coma and is not responsive to external stimuli is referred to as "alpha coma".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] "Ultra-slow" or "near-DC" activity is recorded using DC amplifiers in some research contexts.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It is not typically recorded in a clinical context because the signal at these frequencies is susceptible to a number of artifacts.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Some features of the EEG are transient rather than rhythmic.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Spikes and sharp waves may represent seizure activity or interictal activity in individuals with epilepsy or a predisposition toward epilepsy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Other transient features are normal: vertex waves and sleep spindles are seen in normal sleep.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] There are types of activity that are statistically uncommon, but not associated with dysfunction or disease.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] These are often referred to as "normal variants".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The mu rhythm is an example of a normal variant.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The normal electroencephalogram (EEG) varies by age.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The prenatal EEG and neonatal EEG is quite different from the adult EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Fetuses in the third trimester and newborns display two common brain activity patterns: "discontinuous" and "trace alternant." "Discontinuous" electrical activity refers to sharp bursts of electrical activity followed by low frequency waves.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] "Trace alternant" electrical activity describes sharp bursts followed by short high amplitude intervals and usually indicates quiet sleep in newborns.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG in childhood generally has slower frequency oscillations than the adult EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The normal EEG also varies depending on state.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG is used along with other measurements (EOG, EMG) to define sleep stages in polysomnography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Stage I sleep (equivalent to drowsiness in some systems) appears on the EEG as drop-out of the posterior basic rhythm.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] There can be an increase in theta frequencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Santamaria and Chiappa cataloged a number of the variety of patterns associated with drowsiness.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Stage II sleep is characterized by sleep spindles – transient runs of rhythmic activity in the 12–14 Hz range (sometimes referred to as the "sigma" band) that have a frontal-central maximum.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Most of the activity in Stage II is in the 3–6 Hz range.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Stage III and IV sleep are defined by the presence of delta frequencies and are often referred to collectively as "slow-wave sleep".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Stages I–IV comprise non-REM (or "NREM") sleep.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG in REM (rapid eye movement) sleep appears somewhat similar to the awake EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] EEG under general anesthesia depends on the type of anesthetic employed.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Anesthetic effects on EEG signals are beginning to be understood at the level of drug actions on different kinds of synapses and the circuits that allow synchronized neuronal activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Recent algorithms based on state-chart representation using EEG signals can now to monitor the brain states during general anesthesia allowing to classify the brain depth under various sedation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] EEG is an extremely useful technique for studying brain activity, but the signal measured is always contaminated by artifacts which can impact the analysis of the data.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] An artifact is any measured signal that does not originate within the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Although multiple algorithms exist for the removal of artifacts, the problem of how to deal with them remains an open question.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The source of artifacts can be from issues relating to the instrument, such as faulty electrodes, line noise or high electrode impedance, or they may be from the physiology of the subject being recorded.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] This can include, eye blinks and movement, cardiac activity and muscle activity and these types of artifacts are more complicated to remove.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Artifacts may bias the visual interpretation of EEG data as some may mimic cognitive activity that could affect diagnoses of problems such as Alzheimer's disease or sleep disorders.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] As such the removal of such artifacts in EEG data used for practical applications is of the utmost importance.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It is important to be able to distinguish artifacts from genuine brain activity in order to prevent incorrect interpretations of EEG data.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] General approaches for the removal of artifacts from the data are, prevention, rejection and cancellation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The goal of any approach is to develop methodology capable of identifying and removing artifacts without affecting the quality of the EEG signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] As artifact sources are quite different the majority of researchers focus on developing algorithms that will identify and remove a single type of noise in the signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Simple filtering using a notch filter is commonly employed to reject components with a 50/60 Hz frequency.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] However such simple filters are not an appropriate choice for dealing with all artifacts, as for some, their frequencies will overlap with the EEG frequencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Regression algorithms have a moderate computation cost and are simple.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] They represented the most popular correction method up until the mid-1990s when they were replaced by "blind source separation" type methods.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Regression algorithms work on the premise that all artifacts are comprised by one or more reference channels.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Subtracting these reference channels from the other contaminated channels, in either the time or frequency domain, by estimating the impact of the reference channels on the other channels, would correct the channels for the artifact.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Although the requirement of reference channels ultimately lead to this class of algorithm being replaced, they still represent the benchmark against which modern algorithms are evaluated.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Blind source separation (BSS) algorithms employed to remove artifacts include principal component analysis (PCA) and independent component analysis (ICA) and several algorithms in this class have been successful at tackling most physiological artifacts.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Recent real-time algorithms based on wavelet transport called wavelet quantile normalisation (WQN) can now be used to find and replace artifact segment in real-time in the absence of artifact information.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Ocular artifacts affect the EEG signal significantly.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] This is due to eye movements involving a change in electric fields surrounding the eyes, distorting the electric field over the scalp, and as EEG is recorded on the scalp, it therefore distorts the recorded signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] A difference of opinion exists among researchers, with some arguing ocular artifacts are, or may be reasonably described as a single generator, whilst others argue it is important to understand the potentially complicated mechanisms.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Three potential mechanisms have been proposed to explain the ocular artifact.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The first is corneal retinal dipole movement which argues that an electric dipole is formed between the cornea and retina, as the former is positively and the latter negatively charged.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] When the eye moves, so does this dipole which impacts the electrical field over the scalp, this is the most standard view.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The second mechanism is retinal dipole movement, which is similar to the first but differing in that it argues there is a potential difference, hence dipole across the retina with the cornea having little effect.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It is known that there is a change in voltage around the eyes when the eyelid moves, even if the eyeball does not.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It is thought that the eyelid can be described as a sliding potential source and that the impacting of blinking is different to eye movement on the recorded EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Eyelid fluttering artifacts of a characteristic type were previously called Kappa rhythm (or Kappa waves).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It is usually seen in the prefrontal leads, that is, just over the eyes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Sometimes they are seen with mental activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] They are usually in the Theta (4–7 Hz) or Alpha (7–14 Hz) range.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] They were named because they were believed to originate from the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Later study revealed they were generated by rapid fluttering of the eyelids, sometimes so minute that it was difficult to see.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] They are in fact noise in the EEG reading, and should not technically be called a rhythm or wave.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Therefore, current usage in electroencephalography refers to the phenomenon as an eyelid fluttering artifact, rather than a Kappa rhythm (or wave).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The propagation of the ocular artifact is impacted by multiple factors including the properties of the subject's skull, neuronal tissues and skin but the signal may be approximated as being inversely proportional to the distance from the eyes squared.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The electrooculogram (EOG) consists of a series of electrodes measuring voltage changes close to the eye and is the most common tool for dealing with the eye movement artifact in the EEG signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Another source of artifacts are various muscle movements across the body.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] This particular class of artifact is usually recorded by all electrodes on the scalp due to myogenic activity (increase or decrease of blood pressure).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The origin of these artifacts have no single location and arises from functionally independent muscle groups, meaning the characteristics of the artifact are not constant.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The observed patterns due to muscular artifacts will change depending on subject sex, the particular muscle tissue, and its degree of contraction.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The frequency range for muscular artifacts is wide and overlaps with every classic EEG rhythm.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] However most of the power is concentrated in the lower range of the observed frequencies of 20 to 300 Hz making the gamma band particularly susceptible to muscular artifacts.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Some muscle artifacts may have activity with a frequency as low as 2 Hz, so delta and theta bands may also be affected by muscle activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Muscular artifacts may impact sleep studies, as unconscious bruxism (grinding of teeth) movements or snoring can seriously impact the quality of the recorded EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In addition the recordings made of epilepsy patients may be significantly impacted by the existence of muscular artifacts.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The potential due to cardiac activity introduces electrocardiograph (ECG) errors in the EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Artifacts arising due to cardiac activity may be removed with the help of an ECG reference signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Glossokinetic artifacts are caused by the potential difference between the base and the tip of the tongue.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Minor tongue movements can contaminate the EEG, especially in parkinsonian and tremor disorders.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In addition to artifacts generated by the body, many artifacts originate from outside the body.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Movement by the patient, or even just settling of the electrodes, may cause *electrode pops*, spikes originating from a momentary change in the impedance of a given electrode.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Poor grounding of the EEG electrodes can cause significant 50 or 60 Hz artifact, depending on the local power system's frequency.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] A third source of possible interference can be the presence of an IV drip; such devices can cause rhythmic, fast, low-voltage bursts, which may be confused for spikes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Abnormal activity can broadly be separated into epileptiform and non-epileptiform activity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It can also be separated into focal or diffuse.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Focal epileptiform discharges represent fast, synchronous potentials in a large number of neurons in a somewhat discrete area of the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] These can occur as interictal activity, between seizures, and represent an area of cortical irritability that may be predisposed to producing epileptic seizures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Interictal discharges are not wholly reliable for determining whether a patient has epilepsy nor where his/her seizure might originate.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Generalized epileptiform discharges often have an anterior maximum, but these are seen synchronously throughout the entire brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] They are strongly suggestive of a generalized epilepsy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Focal non-epileptiform abnormal activity may occur over areas of the brain where there is focal damage of the cortex or white matter.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It often consists of an increase in slow frequency rhythms or a loss of normal higher frequency rhythms.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It may also appear as focal or unilateral decrease in amplitude of the EEG signal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Diffuse non-epileptiform abnormal activity may manifest as diffuse abnormally slow rhythms or bilateral slowing of normal rhythms, such as the PBR.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Intracortical Encephalogram electrodes and sub-dural electrodes can be used in tandem to discriminate and discretize artifact from epileptiform and other severe neurological events.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] More advanced measures of abnormal EEG signals have also recently received attention as possible biomarkers for different disorders such as Alzheimer's disease.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Systems for decoding imagined speech from EEG have applications such as in brain–computer interfaces.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The Department of Defense (DoD) and Veteran's Affairs (VA), and U.S Army Research Laboratory (ARL), collaborated on EEG diagnostics in order to detect mild to moderate Traumatic Brain Injury (mTBI) in combat soldiers.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Between 2000 and 2012, 75 percent of U.S. military operations brain injuries were classified mTBI.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In response, the DoD pursued new technologies capable of rapid, accurate, non-invasive, and field-capable detection of mTBI to address this injury.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Combat personnel often develop PTSD and mTBI in correlation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Both conditions present with altered low-frequency brain wave oscillations.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Altered brain waves from PTSD patients present with decreases in low-frequency oscillations, whereas, mTBI injuries are linked to increased low-frequency wave oscillations.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Effective EEG diagnostics can help doctors accurately identify conditions and appropriately treat injuries in order to mitigate long-term effects.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Traditionally, clinical evaluation of EEGs involved visual inspection.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Instead of a visual assessment of brain wave oscillation topography, quantitative electroencephalography (qEEG), computerized algorithmic methodologies, analyzes a specific region of the brain and transforms the data into a meaningful "power spectrum" of the area.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Accurately differentiating between mTBI and PTSD can significantly increase positive recovery outcomes for patients especially since long-term changes in neural communication can persist after an initial mTBI incident.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Another common measurement made from EEG data is that of complexity measures such as Lempel-Ziv complexity, fractal dimension, and spectral flatness, which are associated with particular pathologies or pathology stages.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Inexpensive EEG devices exist for the low-cost research and consumer markets.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Recently, a few companies have miniaturized medical grade EEG technology to create versions accessible to the general public.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Some of these companies have built commercial EEG devices retailing for less than US$100.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG has been used for many purposes besides the conventional uses of clinical diagnosis and conventional cognitive neuroscience.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] An early use was during World War II by the U.S.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Army Air Corps to screen out pilots in danger of having seizures; long-term EEG recordings in epilepsy patients are still used today for seizure prediction.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Neurofeedback remains an important extension, and in its most advanced form is also attempted as the basis of brain computer interfaces.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG is also used quite extensively in the field of neuromarketing.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The EEG is altered by drugs that affect brain functions, the chemicals that are the basis for psychopharmacology.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Berger's early experiments recorded the effects of drugs on EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The science of pharmaco-electroencephalography has developed methods to identify substances that systematically alter brain functions for therapeutic and recreational use.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Honda is attempting to develop a system to enable an operator to control its Asimo robot using EEG, a technology it eventually hopes to incorporate into its automobiles.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] EEGs have been used as evidence in criminal trials in the Indian state of Maharashtra.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Brain Electrical Oscillation Signature Profiling (BEOS), an EEG technique, was used in the trial of *State of Maharashtra v.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Sharma* to show Sharma remembered using arsenic to poison her ex-fiancé, although the reliability and scientific basis of BEOS is disputed.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] A lot of research is currently being carried out in order to make EEG devices smaller, more portable and easier to use.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] So called "Wearable EEG" is based upon creating low power wireless collection electronics and 'dry' electrodes which do not require a conductive gel to be used.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Wearable EEG aims to provide small EEG devices which are present only on the head and which can record EEG for days, weeks, or months at a time, as ear-EEG.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Such prolonged and easy-to-use monitoring could make a step change in the diagnosis of chronic conditions such as epilepsy, and greatly improve the end-user acceptance of BCI systems.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Research is also being carried out on identifying specific solutions to increase the battery lifetime of Wearable EEG devices through the use of the data reduction approach.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In research, currently EEG is often used in combination with machine learning.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] EEG data are pre-processed then passed on to machine learning algorithms.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] These algorithms are then trained to recognize different diseases like schizophrenia, epilepsy or dementia.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Furthermore, they are increasingly used to study seizure detection.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] By using machine learning, the data can be analyzed automatically.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In the long run this research is intended to build algorithms that support physicians in their clinical practice and to provide further insights into diseases.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In this vein, complexity measures of EEG data are often calculated, such as Lempel-Ziv complexity, fractal dimension, and spectral flatness.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It has been shown that combining or multiplying such measures can reveal previously hidden information in EEG data.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] EEG signals from musical performers were used to create instant compositions and one CD by the Brainwave Music Project, run at the Computer Music Center at Columbia University by Brad Garton and Dave Soldier.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Similarly, an hour-long recording of the brainwaves of Ann Druyan was included on the Voyager Golden Record, launched on the *Voyager* probes in 1977, in case any extraterrestrial intelligence could decode her thoughts, which included what it was like to fall in love.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1875, Richard Caton (1842–1926), a physician practicing in Liverpool, presented his findings about electrical phenomena of the exposed cerebral hemispheres of rabbits and monkeys in the *British Medical Journal*.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1890, Polish physiologist Adolf Beck published an investigation of spontaneous electrical activity of the brain of rabbits and dogs that included rhythmic oscillations altered by light.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Beck started experiments on the electrical brain activity of animals.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Beck placed electrodes directly on the surface of the brain to test for sensory stimulation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] His observation of fluctuating brain activity led to the conclusion of brain waves.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1912, Ukrainian physiologist Vladimir Vladimirovich Pravdich-Neminsky published the first animal EEG and the evoked potential of the mammalian (dog).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1914, Napoleon Cybulski and Jelenska-Macieszyna photographed EEG recordings of experimentally induced seizures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] German physiologist and psychiatrist Hans Berger (1873–1941) recorded the first human EEG in 1924.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Expanding on work previously conducted on animals by Richard Caton and others, Berger also invented the electroencephalograph (giving the device its name), an invention described "as one of the most surprising, remarkable, and momentous developments in the history of clinical neurology".
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] His discoveries were first confirmed by British scientists Edgar Douglas Adrian and B.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1934, Fisher and Lowenbach first demonstrated epileptiform spikes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1935, Gibbs, Davis and Lennox described interictal spike waves and the three cycles/s pattern of clinical absence seizures, which began the field of clinical electroencephalography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Subsequently, in 1936 Gibbs and Jasper reported the interictal spike as the focal signature of epilepsy.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The same year, the first EEG laboratory opened at Massachusetts General Hospital.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Franklin Offner (1911–1999), professor of biophysics at Northwestern University developed a prototype of the EEG that incorporated a piezoelectric inkwriter called a Crystograph (the whole device was typically known as the Offner Dynograph).
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1947, The American EEG Society was founded and the first International EEG congress was held.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In 1953 Aserinsky and Kleitman described REM sleep.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] In the 1950s, William Grey Walter developed an adjunct to EEG called EEG topography, which allowed for the mapping of electrical activity across the surface of the brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] This enjoyed a brief period of popularity in the 1980s and seemed especially promising for psychiatry.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It was never accepted by neurologists and remains primarily a research tool.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] An electroencephalograph system manufactured by Beckman Instruments was used on at least one of the Project Gemini crewed spaceflights (1965–1966) to monitor the brain waves of astronauts on the flight.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] It was one of many Beckman Instruments specialized for and used by NASA.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The first instance of the use of EEG to control a physical object, a robot, was in 1988.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] The robot would follow a line or stop depending on the alpha activity of the subject.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] If the subject relaxed and closed their eyes therefore increasing alpha activity, the bot would move.
[src:marianne-gullberg/eeg-p02] Opening their eyes thus decreasing alpha activity would cause the robot to stop on the trajectory.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] EMA is used in linguistics and speech pathology to study articulation and in medicine to study oropharyngeal dysphagia.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Other methods have been used to study articulation and ingestion with tradeoffs in the kind and amount of data available.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Palatography allows the study of articulations that make contact with the palate such as some lingual consonants, but unlike EMA, palatographs cannot provide data on sounds which do not make contact such as vowels.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Fluoroscopy and X-ray microbeam allow the investigation of non-contact movements of the mouth like EMA, but expose subjects to ionizing radiation which limits the amount of data that can be collected from a given participant.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The ability to observe the movements of articulators has been of great importance to the study of phonetics in order to understand the way sounds are produced.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Electromagnetic articulography uses the principle of electromagnetic induction to measure the position and movement of various points in and around the mouth.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] A helmet containing electromagnetic transmitters creates a variable magnetic field by running currents through the transmitters at different frequencies.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Sensor coils placed midsagittally in the mouth produce current as they move through the magnetic field inversely proportional to the cube of the distance from the transmitters.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The current induced alternates at the same frequency as the transmitter coil and the composite signal can be separated out to determine the distance from each individual coil, thus determining the position of the sensor in space.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] In two-dimensional articulography, transmitter coils are placed in an equilateral triangle along the midsagittal plane at the forehead, chin, and neck.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Because of the geometric orientation of the transmitter coils, accurate readings are able to be taken as long as the sensor coils placed on the tongue stay within about a centimeter of the midsagittal plane and are not angled at more than 30 degrees.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Articulographs able to measure in three dimensions use six transmitter coils organized in a spherical configuration.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The transmitters are arranged so that the axis of a sensor coil is never perpendicular to more than three transmitters.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Through the transmitter configuration and ability to measure in multiple dimensions, three-dimensional articulographs are able to make measurements outside of the midsagittal plane.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] 2D articulographs require restrictive headmounts to ensure that the subject's head does not move off the plane of measurement.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Because 3D articulographs are able to measure outside of the midsagittal plane, a less restrictive headmount is able to be used.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Thomas Hixon was the first to describe the use of electromagnetic principles to measure articulation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] In his 1971 letter to the editor, published in *The Journal of the Acoustical Society of America*, he described a setup using two sensor coils and one generator coil.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The sensor coils, attached to the forehead and back of the neck, would remain stationary while the generator coil, attached to the jaw, would move creating variable currents in the sensor coils.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] These currents could then be used to determine the distance in two dimensions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Early EMA systems like Hixon's had problems with accounting for tilting of the tongue during use as tilting of the sensor coils causes changes in the induced current that can skew data.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] In 1987, Paul Schönle et al. published an improved system that used three transmitter coils (analogous to Hixon's generator coil) and computer software to triangulate the position of sensor coils and account for tilt.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] However modern two-dimensional systems are still unable to compensate for tilting of sensors past 30 degrees and measurement is distorted if sensor coils are moved off the centerline of the mouth.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] In 1993, Andreas Zierdt published a description of an articulograph that would be able to measure movement in three dimensions, though three dimensional articulographs have only been commercially available since around 2009.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Zierdt's conceptualization placed six transmitter coils equidistant from each other.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] As sensor coils are placed on the tongue of the subject, articulation may be affected depending on the placement of the coils, but no comparative analysis has shown whether articulation is altered because of the coils.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The coils are about 3 mm in size and are not considered to be a particularly large source of error for measurements.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Some researchers have found that subjects are irritated by sensor coils placed on the tip of the tongue which can lead to disturbed articulation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Similarly, the wires attached to the sensor coils can inhibit articulation if not run out the side of the mouth.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] It has not been shown that long term exposure to electromagnetic fields is harmful to human health, but it is recommended to avoid subjects who are pregnant or who utilize pacemakers.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Guidelines place the limit for safe continuous exposure between 100 μT and 200 μT.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] The field and frequencies output by electromagnetic articulographs are comparable to those put out by computer terminals with the maximum measured being about 10 μT.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Various diagnostic techniques preceded electromagnetic articulography.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Palatography and electropalatography both measure contact of the tongue with the palate and thus are unable to measure articulations that do not make contact with the palate such as vowels.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Palatography involves the painting of a colored substance onto the tongue which is then transferred onto the palate during articulation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] A picture is then taken of the palate to record the location of contact and, if another palatogram is to be taken, the mouth is washed out and the tongue repainted.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] A particularly low cost method that is often used in fieldwork, it can be difficult to collect large amounts of data.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Electropalatography involves the use of a custom-fitted artificial palate containing electrodes that measure contact.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] While able to record multiple contacts, the artificial palate may obstruct or interfere with articulation, and each subject requires a custom-fitted palate.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Video fluoroscopy uses X-ray radiation to produce moving pictures of the mouth during articulation or swallowing.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] It is considered the gold standard in studies of dysphagia because of its ability to take videos of the entire digestive tract during swallowing events.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] It is often used to study and treat aspiration of food, what parts of the digestive tract are malfunctioning during swallowing, and positions in which swallowing is easiest.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Only limited data is able to be collected as sessions are typically limited to three minutes due to the hazards of radiation exposure. and it does not allow for fine grain analysis of tongue movements.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Similar to video fluoroscopy, X-ray microbeam studies use radiation to study movements of articulators.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Gold pellets, 2 to 3 mm in size, are placed in and around the mouth similar to the coils used in EMA.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Radiation exposure is limited by using computer software to focus narrow X-ray beams, about 6 mm2, on the pellets and track them as they move.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] Like EMA, X-ray microbeam studies are limited by the placement of the pellets.
[src:marianne-gullberg/electromagnetic-articulography] While able to minimize radiation exposure, the system is largely inaccessible as it is unique to the University of Wisconsin.
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] The **European Second Language Association** (EuroSLA) is a learned society for researchers with an interest in second language and second language acquisition.
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] EuroSLA was established in Colchester, the United Kingdom, in 1989 and the first president of the society was Vivian Cook.
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] The 2024 president is Roger Gilabert (University of Barcelona).
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] The *Journal of the European Second Language Association* (ISSN 2399-9101) is published after the annual conferences.
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] The *EUROSLA Yearbook* has been published annually by the John Benjamins Publishing Company since 2000.
[src:marianne-gullberg/european-second-language-association] The association presents a yearly "best article prize" and a career award "for outstanding scholarship and contribution to the field".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A **gesture** is a form of nonverbal communication or non-vocal communication in which visible bodily actions communicate particular messages, either in place of, or in conjunction with, speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures include movement of the hands, face, or other parts of the body.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures differ from physical non-verbal communication that does not communicate specific messages, such as purely expressive displays, proxemics, or displays of joint attention.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures allow individuals to communicate a variety of feelings and thoughts, from contempt and hostility to approval and affection, often together with body language in addition to words when they speak.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gesticulation and speech work independently of each other, but join to provide emphasis and meaning.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gesture processing takes place in areas of the brain such as Broca's and Wernicke's areas, which are used by speech and sign language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In fact, language is thought by some scholars to have evolved in *Homo sapiens* from an earlier system consisting of manual gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The theory that language evolved from manual gestures, termed Gestural Theory, dates back to the work of 18th-century philosopher and priest Abbé de Condillac, and has been revived by contemporary anthropologist Gordon W.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Hewes, in 1973, as part of a discussion on the origin of language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures have been studied throughout time from different philosophers.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Marcus Fabius Quintilianus was a Roman Rhetorician who studied in his Institutio Oratoria on how gesture can be used on rhetorical discourses.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] One of his greatest works and foundation for communication was the "Institutio Oratoria" where he explains his observations and nature of different oratories.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A study done in 1644, by John Bulwer an English physician and early Baconian natural philosopher wrote five works exploring human communications pertaining to gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Bulwer analyzed dozens of gestures and provided a guide under his book named Chirologia which focused on hand gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In the 19th century, Andrea De Jorio an Italian antiquarian who considered a lot of research about body language published an extensive account of gesture expressions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Meltzoff an American psychologist internationally renown for infant and child development conducted a study in 1977 on the imitation of facial and manual gestures by newborns.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The study concluded that "infants between 12 and 21 days of age can imitate the facial and manual gestures of parents".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A peer-reviewed journal Gesture has been published since 2001, and was founded by Adam Kendon and Cornelia Müller.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The International Society for Gesture Studies (ISGS) was founded in 2002.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gesture has frequently been taken up by researchers in the field of dance studies and performance studies in ways that emphasize the ways they are culturally and contextually inflected.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Performance scholar Carrie Noland describes gestures as "learned techniques of the body" and stresses the way gestures are embodied corporeal forms of cultural communication.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] But rather than just residing within one cultural context, she describes how gestures migrate across bodies and locations to create new cultural meanings and associations.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] She also posits how they might function as a form of "resistance to homogenization" because they are so dependent on the specification of the bodies that perform them.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gesture has also been taken up within queer theory, ethnic studies and their intersections in performance studies, as a way to think about how the moving body gains social meaning.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] José Esteban Muñoz uses the idea of gesture to mark a kind of refusal of finitude and certainty and links gesture to his ideas of ephemera.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Muñoz specifically draws on the African-American dancer and drag queen performer Kevin Aviance to articulate his interest not in what queer gestures might mean, but what they might perform.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Juana María Rodríguez borrows ideas of phenomenology and draws on Noland and Muñoz to investigate how gesture functions in queer sexual practices as a way to rewrite gender and negotiate power relations.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] She also connects gesture to Giorgio Agamben's idea of "means without ends" to think about political projects of social justice that are incomplete, partial, and legibile within culturally and socially defined spheres of meaning.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Since the late 1990s, most research has revolved around the contrasting hypothesis that Lexical gestures serve a primarily cognitive purpose in aiding the process of speech production.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] As of 2012, there is research to suggest that Lexical Gesture does indeed serve a primarily communicative purpose and cognitive only secondary, but in the realm of socio-pragmatic communication, rather than lexico-semantic modification.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Humans have the ability to communicate through language, but they can also express through gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In particular, gestures can be transmitted through movements of body parts, face, and body expressions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Researchers Goldin Meadow and Brentari D. conducted research in 2015 and concluded that communicating through sign language is no different from spoken language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The first way to distinguish between categories of gesture is to differentiate between communicative gesture and informative gesture.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] While most gestures can be defined as possibly happening during the course of spoken utterances, the informative-communicative dichotomy focuses on intentionality of meaning and communication in co-speech gesture.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Informative gestures are passive gestures that provide information about the speaker as a person and not about what the speaker is trying to communicate.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Some movements are not purely considered gestures, however a person could perform these adapters in such way like scratching, adjusting clothing, and tapping.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These gestures can occur during speech, but they may also occur independently of communication, as they are not a part of active communication.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] While informative gestures may communicate information about the person speaking (e.g. itchy, uncomfortable, etc.), this communication is not engaged with any language being produced by the person gesturing.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Army recruitment poster of Uncle Sam, he is pointing and sending a non-verbal form of gesture by implying he wants the viewer to join the U.S.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This is a form of symbolic gesture, usually used in the absence of speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Body language is a form of nonverbal communication that allows visual cues that transmit messages without speaking.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are movement that are made with the body: arms, hands, facial, etc.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Barbara and Allan Pease, authors of *The Definitive Book of Body Language*, concluded that everyone does a shoulder shrug, a gesture signifying that the person is not comprehending what they are supposed to be understanding.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Also, that showing the palms of both hands to show a person is not hiding anything, and raising the eyebrows to indicate a greeting.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Finger gestures are commonly used in a variety of ways, from point at something to indicate that you want to show a person something to indicating a thumbs up to show everything is good.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Some gestures are near universals, i.e., found all over the world with only some exceptions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] An example is the head shake to signify "no".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Also, in most cultures nodding your head signifies "Yes", which the book "The Definitive Book of Body Language" describes as submissive gesture to representing the conversation is going the direction of the person speaking.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The book explains that people who are born deaf can show a form of submissive gesture to signify "Yes".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Within the realm of communicative gestures, the first distinction to be made is between gestures made with the hands and arms, and gestures made with other parts of the body.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Examples of Non-manual gestures may include head nodding and shaking, shoulder shrugging, and facial expression, among others.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Non-manual gestures are attested in languages all around the world, but have not been the primary focus of most research regarding co-speech gesture.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A gesture that is a form of communication in which bodily actions communicate particular messages.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The most familiar are the so-called emblems or quotable gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These are conventional, culture-specific gestures that can be used as replacement for words, such as the handwave used in the US for "hello" and "goodbye".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A single emblematic gesture can have a very different significance in different cultural contexts, ranging from complimentary to highly offensive.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The page List of gestures discusses emblematic gestures made with one hand, two hands, hand and other body parts, and body and facial gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Symbolic gestures can occur either concurrently or independently of vocal speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Symbolic gestures are iconic gestures that are widely recognized, fixed, and have conventionalized meanings.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Deictic gestures can occur simultaneously with vocal speech or in place of it.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Deictic gestures are gestures that consist of indicative or pointing motions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These gestures often work in the same way as demonstrative words and pronouns like "this" or "that".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Deictic gestures can refer to concrete or intangible objects or people.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Motor or beat gestures usually consist of short, repetitive, rhythmic movements that are closely tied with prosody in verbal speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Unlike symbolic and deictic gestures, beat gestures cannot occur independently of verbal speech and convey no semantic information.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] For example, some people wave their hands as they speak to emphasize a certain word or phrase.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These gestures are closely coordinated with speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The so-called beat gestures are used in conjunction with speech and keep time with the rhythm of speech to emphasize certain words or phrases.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These types of gestures are integrally connected to speech and thought processes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Other spontaneous gestures used during speech production known as iconic gestures are more full of content, and may echo, or elaborate, the meaning of the co-occurring speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] They depict aspects of spatial images, actions, people, or objects.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] For example, a gesture that depicts the act of throwing may be synchronous with the utterance, "He threw the ball right into the window." Such gestures that are used along with speech tend to be universal.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] For example, one describing that they are feeling cold due to a lack of proper clothing and/or a cold weather can accompany their verbal description with a visual one.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This can be achieved through various gestures such as by demonstrating a shiver and/or by rubbing the hands together.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The elaboration of lexical gestures falls on a spectrum of iconic-metaphorical in how closely tied they are to the lexico-semantic content of the verbal speech they coordinate with.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Lexical gestures, like motor gestures, cannot occur independently of verbal speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The purpose of lexical gestures is still widely contested in the literature with some linguists arguing that lexical gestures serve to amplify or modulate the semantic content of lexical speech, or that it serves a cognitive purpose in aiding in lexical access and retrieval or verbal working memory.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Most recent research suggests that lexical gestures serve a primarily socio-pragmatic role.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Studies affirm a strong link between gesture typology and language development.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Young children under the age of two seem to rely on pointing gestures to refer to objects that they do not know the names of.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Once the words are learned, they eschewed those referential (pointing) gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] One would think that the use of gesture would decrease as the child develops spoken language, but results reveal that gesture frequency increased as speaking frequency increased with age.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] There is, however, a change in gesture typology at different ages, suggesting a connection between gestures and language development.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Children most often use pointing and adults rely more on iconic and beat gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] As children begin producing sentence-like utterances, they also begin producing new kinds of gestures that adults use when speaking (iconics and beats).
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Evidence of this systematic organization of gesture is indicative of its association to language development.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestural languages such as American Sign Language operate as complete natural languages that are gestural in modality.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] They should not be confused with finger spelling, in which a set of emblematic gestures are used to represent a written alphabet.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Sign languages are different from gesturing in that concepts are modeled by certain hand motions or expressions and has a specific established structure while gesturing is more malleable and has no specific structure rather it supplements speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Before an established sign language was created in Nicaragua after the 1970s, deaf Nicaraguans would use "home signs" in order to communicate with others.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] These home signs were not part of a unified language but were still used as familiar motions and expressions used within their family—still closely related to language rather than gestures with no specific structure.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Home signs are similar to the gestural actions of chimpanzees.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are used by these animals in place of verbal language, which is restricted in animals due to their lacking certain physiological and articulation abilities that humans have for speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The function of gestures may have been a significant player in the evolution of language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gesturing is probably universal; there has been no report of a community that does not gesture.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are a crucial part of everyday conversation such as chatting, describing a route, negotiating prices on a market; they are ubiquitous.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are learned embodied cultural practices that can function as a way to interpret ethnic, gender, and sexual identity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures, commonly referred to as "body language", play an important role in industry.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Proper body language etiquette in business dealings can be crucial for success.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] However, gestures can have different meanings according to the country in which they are expressed.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In an age of global business, diplomatic cultural sensitivity has become a necessity.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures that we take as innocent may be seen by someone else as deeply insulting.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are also a means to initiate a mating ritual.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This may include elaborate dances and other movements.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures play a major role in many aspects of human life.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Additionally, when people use gestures, there is a certain shared background knowledge.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Different cultures use similar gestures when talking about a specific action such as how we gesture the idea of drinking out of a cup.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] When an individual makes a gesture, another person can understand because of recognition of the actions/shapes.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures have been documented in the arts such as in Greek vase paintings, Indian Miniatures or European paintings.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures play a central role in religious or spiritual rituals.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In Hinduism and Buddhism, a *mudra* (Sanskrit, literally "seal", "gesture" or "attitude") is a symbolic gesture made with the hand, body or mind.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Each mudra has a specific meaning, and is associated with a specific spiritual quality or state.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In yoga, mudras are considered to be higher practices which lead to awakening of the pranas, chakras and kundalini, and which can bestow major siddhis, psychic powers, on the advanced practitioner.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In Hindu and Buddhist iconography mudras play a central role.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] For example, Vitarka Vicara, the gesture of discussion and transmission of Buddhist teaching, is done by joining the tips of the thumb and the index together, while keeping the other fingers straight.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] A common Christian religious gesture is crossing oneself as a sign of respect, also known as making the sign of the cross; often this is accompanied by kneeling before a sacred object.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In the renewal of the Catholic liturgy promoted by the Second Vatican Council in the 1960s, "actions, gestures, and bodily attitudes" were noted as means by which a whole worshipping community could participate in the liturgical action.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are processed in the same areas of the brain as speech and sign language such as the left inferior frontal gyrus (Broca's area) and the posterior middle temporal gyrus, posterior superior temporal sulcus and superior temporal gyrus (Wernicke's area).
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] It has been suggested that these parts of the brain originally supported the pairing of gesture and meaning and then were adapted in human evolution "for the comparable pairing of sound and meaning as voluntary control over the vocal apparatus was established and spoken language evolved".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] As a result, it underlies both symbolic gesture and spoken language in the present human brain.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Their common neurological basis also supports the idea that symbolic gesture and spoken language are two parts of a single fundamental semiotic system that underlies human discourse.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The linkage of hand and body gestures in conjunction with speech is further revealed by the nature of gesture use in blind individuals during conversation.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This phenomenon uncovers a function of gesture that goes beyond portraying communicative content of language and extends David McNeill's view of the gesture-speech system.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This suggests that gesture and speech work tightly together, and a disruption of one (speech or gesture) will cause a problem in the other.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Studies have found strong evidence that speech and gesture are innately linked in the brain and work in an efficiently wired and choreographed system.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] McNeill's view of this linkage in the brain is just one of three currently up for debate; the others declaring gesture to be a "support system" of spoken language or a physical mechanism for lexical retrieval.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Because of this connection of co-speech gestures—a form of manual action—in language in the brain, Roel Willems and Peter Hagoort conclude that both gestures and language contribute to the understanding and decoding of a speaker's encoded message.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Because gestures aided in understanding the relayed message, there was not as great a need for semantic selection or control that would otherwise be required of the listener through Broca's area.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures are a way to represent the thoughts of an individual, which are prompted in working memory.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The researchers found that those with low capacity of working memory who were able to use gestures actually recalled more terms than those with low capacity who were not able to use gestures.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The movement of gestures can be used to interact with technology like computers, using touch or multi-touch popularised by the iPhone, physical movement detection and visual motion capture, used in video game consoles.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] It can be recorded using kinematic methodology.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] In order to better understand the linguistic values that gestures hold, Adam Kendon, a pioneer in gesture research has proposed to look at it as a continuum from less linguistic to fully linguistic.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Using the continuum, speech declines as "the language-like properties of gestural behaviors increase and idiosyncratic gestures are replaced by socially regulated signs".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Gestures of different kinds fall within this continuum and include spontaneous gesticulations, language-like gestures, pantomime, emblems, and sign language.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Spontaneous gesticulations are not evident without the presence of speech, assisting in the process of vocalization, whereas language-like gestures are "iconic and metaphoric, but lack consistency and are context-dependent".
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] "Language-like gesture" implies that the gesture is assuming something linguistic (Loncke, 2013).
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Pantomime falls in the middle of the continuum and requires shared conventions.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] This kind of gesture helps convey information or describe an event.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] Following pantomime are emblems, which have specific meanings to denote "feelings, obscenities, and insults" and are not required to be used in conjunction with speech.
[src:marianne-gullberg/gesture] The most linguistic gesture on Kendon's continuum is sign language, where "single manual signs have specific meanings and are combined with other manual signs according to specific rules".
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Gullberg carried out her doctoral research at Lund University between 1993 and 1997.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] After short-term positions there and at Kristianstad University, she took up a postdoctoral position at the Max Planck Institute for Psycholinguistics in Nijmegen in 2000, where she was appointed Senior Research Scientist in 2003.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] In 2008 she became a tenured associate professor at Radboud University Nijmegen, retaining her research role at the Max Planck Institute and co-founding the Nijmegen Gesture Centre alongside Aslı Özyürek.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] In 2010 she was appointed Professor of Psycholinguistics and Director of the Humanities Lab at Lund University.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Gullberg is a Non-resident Long-term Fellow for Programmes in Languages and Cognitive Science at the Swedish Collegium for Advanced Study in Uppsala, Sweden.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Gullberg is known for her research on language acquisition and gesture.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Her early work reacted against the theory-driven structuralism of Swedish general linguistics at the time by seeking to investigate language use.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Gullberg's research has called into question stereotypes about gesture usage across cultures, such as the idea that Italians use more gestures than speakers of other languages.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] In her work she has drawn on electromagnetic articulography and EEG methods alongside the traditional methods of the humanities, and aims to make a contribution to second language teaching.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] Gullberg has been the recipient of several honours and awards.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] In June 2015 she was elected member of the Royal Swedish Academy of Sciences, and in March 2019 she was awarded the academy's Ann-Kersti and Carl-Hakon Swenson Prize for humanities and social science research.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] She was elected Member of the Academia Europaea in 2017.
[src:marianne-gullberg/marianne-gullberg] In 2019 she was the recipient of the Distinguished Scholar Award of the European Second Language Association, for whom she had previously served as vice-president.
